Testing Responsiveness with DevTools

02
On this page
  1. Turn on the Responsive Feature in Chrome DevTools
  2. Troubleshooting a Lack of Responsiveness
  3. Adding the Viewport Meta Tag

  5. Next Steps

Turn on the Responsive Feature in Chrome DevTools

Chrome DevTools has a responsive feature that can be accessed by clicking the device icon in the upper left corner.

There are several devices presets available for examining the viewport, as well as handles on the side of the preview that allow you to manually resize the window.

Troubleshooting a Lack of Responsiveness

In the screenshot above, DevTools is simulating a phone-sized screen yet the layout hasn’t shifted at all.

If after changing device sizes and zoom levels you still don’t see any reflow changes, the site you’re on might be missing the viewport meta tag in the HTML document <head>.

The viewport meta tag tells the browser on your user’s device how to render the page. There are multiple options you can set to make a page function better on a mobile device.

In this example, setting the content attribute to initial-scale=1 will tell the browser to set the zoom level to 1 when the page is loaded:

<meta name="viewport" content="initial-scale=1" />
<meta name="viewport" content="initial-scale=1" />

If the tag is present, it will be inside the <head> at the top of the HTML page.

Another useful mobile viewport option would be to set width=device-width.

On CampSpots, both the About and Home pages are missing the meta tag.

Adding the Viewport Meta Tag

To fix it, add the viewport meta line from above into the <head> section of the HTML document.

When the viewport meta tag is present, a difference in the presentation of the About page is noticeable in the responsive device viewer. Parts of the page could still look better, but at least it’s a step in the right direction!

Wrapping Up Zooming

In these last couple of lessons, we’ve looked at how our page content can react at different zoom levels and viewport sizes.

While testing emulated viewport sizes is good, testing on real devices is better.

On a Mac, you can tether an iOS device to your desktop with a phone cord and connect to it using Safari’s DevTools. For Android, you can try a similar process with USB Debugging.

Depending on your needs, you could look into commercial cross-browser testing services like BrowserStack or SauceLabs.

Whether you’re the one who will implement fixes or not, it’s worth checking how your app reacts to browser zooming once in a while. If you’re spending time working on layouts or on more complex components, check more often.

Next Steps

If you’re interested in implementing styling fixes, head on over to the Fix Zoom Issues with CSS lesson.

Otherwise, check out how zooming works the fixed version of the CampSpots site then move on to the Screen Reader Testing module.
